The trial of the truck driver, Yandisa Majikija (29), who allegedly crashed into a Hilton father and daughter on the N3 last year has been postponed to June. Majikija made a brief appearance at the Pietermaritzburg Regional Court on Thursday. He is facing two culpable homicide charges after he allegedly crashed into Tony Richter’s bakkie, who was with his daughter, Alice, on the N3 Southbound, near Midmar. The 59-year-old, who was a director of school operations at Hilton College, had stopped to help Alice, whose car had broken down. ALSO READ| Popular Hilton College staff member, Tony Richter, and daughter killed in tragic accident Richter parked his bakkie behind his daughter’s vehicle, which was in the slow lane. They were standing between the two vehicles when the truck hit the bakkie propelling it forward into the pair. Richter died instantly. Alice, who is a yoga teacher, was badly injured. She was rushed to Life Hilton Hospital by paramedics and later underwent surgery, but succumbed to her injuries on the following day. On Thursday the court postponed Majikija’s matter postponed to June 7. The Richter family was also present in court during the proceedings.